<name>Atlanterhavsveien — Atlantic Ocean Road</name>
<description><![CDATA[<h2>Atlanterhavsveien — Atlantic Ocean Road</h2><p><i>Norway · Møre og Romsdal, Kristiansund to Molde</i></p><p><b>Eight bridges leaping between rocky islets — possibly the most photogenic single stretch of road in the world.</b></p><table style='font-family:sans-serif'><tr><td><b>Approx. length:</b></td><td>87 km (54 mi)</td></tr><tr><td><b>Drive time:</b></td><td>2–3 hrs</td></tr><tr><td><b>Best season:</b></td><td>May–September for calm; October–February for storm-watching (genuinely a feature here)</td></tr><tr><td><b>Watch out for:</b></td><td>Waves over the road in storms (locally celebrated, not avoided); slick decks; narrow shoulders; ferry connections to plan around</td></tr><tr><td><b>Track points:</b></td><td>129</td></tr></table><hr><p>The Atlantic Ocean Road proper is just 8 km — eight bridges and several causeways linking Vevang to Kårvåg through a scattering of low rocky islets. The signature bridge, Storseisundet ('the bridge that goes nowhere'), curves and climbs in such a way that from certain angles it looks like the road simply ends in mid-air. Built 1983–89 over a route once served by ferries. Locals come to watch winter storms — waves break over the parapets, and the road is occasionally closed for safety. This longer drive includes the Bremsnes-to-Molde extension via the Hustadvika coastline, with the fishing village of Bud on the way.</p><h3>Scenic points marked on this route:</h3><ul><li><b>Storseisundet Bridge</b> — 260 m cantilever span, 23 m clearance. The 'drunk bridge' that appears to vanish into thin air from certain angles. Best photo: from the path on Eldhusøya, the next island east.</li><li><b>Eldhusøya</b> — Tiny island with a circular boardwalk loop and a café — designed by Norway's National Tourist Routes program. Sea eagles overhead; otters on the rocks.</li><li><b>Bud</b> — Fishing village whose tiny harbor was historically Norway's largest. Ergan Coastal Fort (WWII German installation) preserved as a museum on the headland above.</li><li><b>Molde</b> — 'City of Roses' — known for its 222-peak panorama from the Varden viewpoint above town. Annual jazz festival in July.</li></ul><hr><p><i>Track geometry is interpolated between named waypoints — use a routing service to snap to actual road for navigation. Waypoints, scenic POIs, and notes are reliable.</i></p>]]></description>
